### PHP version

8.5.7

### Browser and operating system

Chrome on Linux and Windows

### Describe the issue you're experiencing

### Overview

After upgrading to PHP 8.5, Livewire triggers a deprecation warning on every subsequent request (update cycle) for components that hold an Eloquent Collection property:

```
ErrorException: Using null as an array offset is deprecated, use an empty string instead
in vendor/laravel/framework/src/Illuminate/Database/Eloquent/Relations/Relation.php:511
```

The issue seems to come from `EloquentCollectionSynth::hydrate()` (line 66). When an Eloquent Collection is dehydrated with an empty collection (`getQueueableClass()` returns `null`), `$meta['modelClass']` is stored as `null`. During hydration, this `null` value is passed directly to `Relation::getMorphedModel($modelClass)`, which uses it as an array key (`static::$morphMap[$alias]`). In PHP 8.5, using `null` as an array offset is deprecated.

### Steps to reproduce:

1. Set up a new Laravel 13 / Livewire 4 app using PHP 8.5
2. Create the component described below and mount it
3. Navigate in your browser to the route where you mounted the component
4. Click the "Refresh" button to trigger a Livewire roundtrip
5. Observe the deprecation warning in logs

### Suggested fix

In `src/Features/SupportModels/EloquentCollectionSynth.php`, line 66:

```php
// Before:
$modelAlias = Relation::getMorphedModel($modelClass);

// After:
$modelAlias = $modelClass ? Relation::getMorphedModel($modelClass) : null;
```

This matches the guard already present in the `dehydrate()` method (line 34: `if ($modelClass) { ... }`).

### Code snippets to reproduce the issue

```php
<?php

use App\Models\User;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Collection;
use Livewire\Component;

class UserList extends Component
{
    public Collection $users;

    public function mount(): void
    {
        $this->users = new Collection();
    }

    public function refresh(): void
    {
        $this->users = User::all();
    }

    public function render()
    {
        return <<<'BLADE'
        <div>
            <button wire:click="refresh()">Refresh</button>
            @foreach($users as $user)
                <p>{{ $user->name }}</p>
            @endforeach
        </div>
        BLADE;
    }
}
```

