### Describe the issue you're experiencing

When user only provide class name (not ability name) as attribute parameter for `#[Authorize]` attribute, the authorization failed/denied. But using component authorization however works as expected.

This is because `AuthorizesRequests` guess the ability from action name and use that against resources map ability from Laravel or policy method.

However, `#[Authorize]` attribute call `Gate` directly that cause authorization failed because there was no parsing for ability name if only class name provided

### Code snippets to reproduce the issue

```php
class PostPolicy
{
    public function createPost(User $user)
    {
        return true;
    }
}
```
```php
